WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.917 --> 00:00:05.831
[high-pitched microphone static]

2
00:00:05.875 --> 00:00:08.138
BENNY: New York. New York!

3
00:00:08.182 --> 00:00:10.749
[whooping]

4
00:00:10.793 --> 00:00:12.403
Oh. my goodness.

5
00:00:12.447 --> 00:00:15.537
I can't even begin to tell
you how overwhelmed I am.

6
00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:18.409
It would be my great honor

7
00:00:18.453 --> 00:00:22.413
to serve as your city's
district attorney!

8
00:00:22.457 --> 00:00:25.634
[applause and cheering]

9
00:00:25.677 --> 00:00:27.766
Now I have to thank
A.D.A. Kenneth Kiehl.

10
00:00:27.810 --> 00:00:29.768
the man behind the man.

11
00:00:29.812 --> 00:00:31.944
I have never run for office.

12
00:00:31.988 --> 00:00:33.729
I've never even considered it.

13
00:00:33.772 --> 00:00:35.470
He showed me the way.

14
00:00:35.513 --> 00:00:36.732
Thank you.

15
00:00:36.775 --> 00:00:38.560
[applause and
cheering]I also have

16
00:00:38.603 --> 00:00:41.128
to thank my sister Isabella.

17
00:00:41.171 --> 00:00:44.435
without whose
encouragement and support

18
00:00:44.479 --> 00:00:46.568
none of this would
have happened.

19
00:00:46.611 --> 00:00:48.744
[applause]And...

20
00:00:48.787 --> 00:00:52.617
I also want to thank
her new. old. husband.

21
00:00:52.661 --> 00:00:54.880
my friend

22
00:00:54.924 --> 00:00:57.927
and my old boss. Dr. Jason Bull.

23
00:00:57.970 --> 00:00:59.972
[applause]

24
00:01:00.016 --> 00:01:01.191
[whooping]

25
00:01:01.235 --> 00:01:03.628
Talk about an end of an era.

26
00:01:03.672 --> 00:01:05.848
[alarm clock blaring]

27
00:01:05.891 --> 00:01:07.806
[alarm stops]IZZY: Jason?

28
00:01:07.850 --> 00:01:10.200
Have you seen her...
her rattle thing?

29
00:01:10.244 --> 00:01:12.681
The pig one or the
cat one? ASTRID: Dada!

30
00:01:12.724 --> 00:01:14.900
The cat one. her favorite one.

31
00:01:14.944 --> 00:01:16.989
Yeah. it's right here
in the bag. Dada. Mama.

32
00:01:17.033 --> 00:01:18.991
You know where you're going?

33
00:01:19.035 --> 00:01:23.431
Uh. the florist. wedding
photographer. party planner.

34
00:01:23.474 --> 00:01:25.128
You know. our wedding
is on Saturday.

35
00:01:25.172 --> 00:01:27.522
and it still feels like we're
just nailing things down.

36
00:01:27.565 --> 00:01:29.872
[laughing]: It seems crazy.

37
00:01:29.915 --> 00:01:32.614
Why don't you take the
SUV? It's right downstairs.

38
00:01:32.657 --> 00:01:34.442
Okay. sure.

39
00:01:34.485 --> 00:01:37.575
Hey. do you want to
go in Daddy's car?

40
00:01:37.619 --> 00:01:40.578
Yeah? Yeah.

41
00:01:40.622 --> 00:01:42.145
[buzzer sounds]

42
00:01:42.189 --> 00:01:43.668
Yes. Tony?

43
00:01:43.712 --> 00:01:45.975
Dr. Bull. your guest is here.

44
00:01:47.977 --> 00:01:49.718
Doctor.

45
00:01:49.761 --> 00:01:52.068
District Attorney Sherman.

46
00:01:52.938 --> 00:01:55.898
Former... District
Attorney Sherman.

47
00:01:57.726 --> 00:01:59.858
I'm vaccinated. You vaccinated?

48
00:01:59.902 --> 00:02:01.860
I am. Oh. good.

49
00:02:01.904 --> 00:02:03.949
Then I'm gonna take
this damn thing off.

50
00:02:03.993 --> 00:02:06.256
Huh. Great minds.Yeah.

51
00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:09.564
Thanks for seeing me.
sneaking me into your home.

52
00:02:09.607 --> 00:02:11.174
Yeah.

53
00:02:11.218 --> 00:02:13.481
David. I just...

54
00:02:13.524 --> 00:02:18.355
I just don't see any way in
the world that I can help you.

55
00:02:18.399 --> 00:02:20.314
I mean. Benny...

56
00:02:20.357 --> 00:02:22.577
He's my lead attorney
and my best friend.

57
00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:25.057
my fiancée's brother. and he

58
00:02:25.101 --> 00:02:28.060
is running to take
over your job. He's

59
00:02:28.104 --> 00:02:31.368
six points ahead in the poll
as of this morning. I just...

60
00:02:31.412 --> 00:02:33.196
I know all that.

61
00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:35.372
but I'm in a fight
for my life. Jason.

62
00:02:35.416 --> 00:02:37.940
I can't go to jail.

63
00:02:37.983 --> 00:02:42.031
I can't do that to
my family. I just

64
00:02:44.033 --> 00:02:46.078
can't.

65
00:02:47.602 --> 00:02:49.212
I need you.

66
00:02:50.387 --> 00:02:51.997
No. you don't.

67
00:02:52.041 --> 00:02:55.044
There are thousands of other
firms out there in the city.

68
00:02:55.087 --> 00:02:57.307
Hmm? What happened to the
one you were working with?

69
00:02:57.351 --> 00:02:59.614
I fired them yesterday.

70
00:03:01.050 --> 00:03:04.880
They wanted me to
settle. and I'm innocent.

71
00:03:04.923 --> 00:03:09.232
Oh. David. I wish that I
could help you here. but...

72
00:03:09.276 --> 00:03:11.713
I don't see any way
of making this work.

73
00:03:11.756 --> 00:03:13.715
Like I said.

74
00:03:13.758 --> 00:03:16.108
I mean. not without
destroying Benny.

75
00:03:16.152 --> 00:03:18.328
I don't think you're
understanding me.

76
00:03:18.372 --> 00:03:20.765
Um

77
00:03:20.809 --> 00:03:23.986
In my entire career.

78
00:03:24.029 --> 00:03:27.772
I never compromised myself.

79
00:03:27.816 --> 00:03:29.948
Except once.

80
00:03:29.992 --> 00:03:32.037
For you.

81
00:03:33.952 --> 00:03:36.955
If you make me go
somewhere else.

82
00:03:36.999 --> 00:03:39.175
I'm gonna have to tell them

83
00:03:39.219 --> 00:03:43.266
about that favor I did
for you eight years ago.

84
00:03:43.310 --> 00:03:45.877
That favor I did
for you and Benny.

85
00:03:45.921 --> 00:03:49.838
And that really
will destroy him.

86
00:03:49.881 --> 00:03:52.536
They'll take away his
license to practice law.

87
00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:54.799
Maybe even find a way to
go after him criminally

88
00:03:54.843 --> 00:03:57.367
after all these years.

89
00:03:58.194 --> 00:04:00.631
Benny doesn't know
about any of that.

90
00:04:00.675 --> 00:04:02.677
Excellent.

91
00:04:03.504 --> 00:04:06.768
Let's keep it that
way. Help me. Jason.

92
00:04:08.509 --> 00:04:11.816
I swear to you...

93
00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:15.124
I am an innocent man.

94
00:04:17.822 --> 00:04:18.780
[elevator bell chimes]

95
00:04:18.823 --> 00:04:20.869
Someone oversleep?

96
00:04:20.912 --> 00:04:22.697
Someone somewhere. I'm sure.

97
00:04:22.740 --> 00:04:24.002
[knocking]

98
00:04:24.046 --> 00:04:26.048
BULL: Who is it?

99
00:04:27.397 --> 00:04:29.704
Hey. Looking for me?

100
00:04:29.747 --> 00:04:31.836
Yes...

101
00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:34.274
I was.

102
00:04:36.363 --> 00:04:39.409
We've been through
a lot. haven't we?

103
00:04:40.410 --> 00:04:44.196
Uh. yeah. yeah.

104
00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:45.633
More than a lot.

105
00:04:45.676 --> 00:04:47.983
Why?

106
00:04:48.026 --> 00:04:51.116
You're not getting all
emotional on me. are you?

107
00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:54.816
Hey. look. I can
still lose this thing.

108
00:04:54.859 --> 00:04:57.340
Polls have been
wrong in the past.

109
00:04:57.384 --> 00:04:59.908
You trust me?

110
00:04:59.951 --> 00:05:02.606
What are you talking about?

111
00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:04.695
Of course I trust you.

112
00:05:04.739 --> 00:05:09.047
I mean. we've virtually spent
every single day together

113
00:05:09.091 --> 00:05:11.136
for the last eight
years. so. yeah.

114
00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:12.877
You're comfortable with me.

115
00:05:12.921 --> 00:05:14.270
we're comfortable
with each other.

116
00:05:14.314 --> 00:05:16.707
but I'm asking you.
do you trust me?

117
00:05:16.751 --> 00:05:18.796
Asked and answered.

118
00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:21.016
Yes. I trust you.

119
00:05:21.059 --> 00:05:23.758
A thousand ways
from Sunday. Yes.

120
00:05:24.933 --> 00:05:27.065
David Sherman came
to see me today.

121
00:05:27.109 --> 00:05:29.894
He wants TAC to
represent him in court.

122
00:05:29.938 --> 00:05:32.332
You serious?

123
00:05:32.375 --> 00:05:35.335
That's crazy. He
knows I work here.

124
00:05:35.378 --> 00:05:37.989
He knows I'm running
to be the new D.A.

125
00:05:38.033 --> 00:05:40.427
I mean. that's... that's crazy.

126
00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:42.385
I know it is. but
here's the thing.

127
00:05:42.429 --> 00:05:45.214
His original defense
team took a poll.

128
00:05:45.257 --> 00:05:48.130
and it turns out 82%

129
00:05:48.173 --> 00:05:50.262
of potential jurors believe

130
00:05:50.306 --> 00:05:52.526
that he resigned
because he was guilty.

131
00:05:52.569 --> 00:05:55.529
And his lawyers urged
him to take a plea.

132
00:05:55.572 --> 00:05:58.662
Makes sense.

133
00:05:58.706 --> 00:06:00.534
Except he's not gonna do that.

134
00:06:00.577 --> 00:06:04.451
because he swears on his
life that he is innocent.

135
00:06:05.669 --> 00:06:07.192
He says he was set up.

136
00:06:07.236 --> 00:06:10.718
I mean. this is a man who. of
his own accord. who resigned

137
00:06:10.761 --> 00:06:13.416
because he thought it would
be better for the city.

138
00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:16.201
He didn't think it would
be fair to the electorate

139
00:06:16.245 --> 00:06:19.074
to have a D.A. who was embroiled

140
00:06:19.117 --> 00:06:21.598
by a court fight he
was in the middle of.

141
00:06:21.642 --> 00:06:23.948
And that is who he is.

142
00:06:23.992 --> 00:06:26.298
I've always liked Dave Sherman.

143
00:06:26.342 --> 00:06:28.257
I've never made a secret of it.

144
00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:31.391
Yeah. Remember how
you and I used to joke

145
00:06:31.434 --> 00:06:34.176
that the only problem
Sherman had as D.A.

146
00:06:34.219 --> 00:06:36.526
is that he was too
nice. too principled?

147
00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:39.616
Well. it turns
out we were right.

148
00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:42.227
Now he wants to
fight this thing.

149
00:06:42.271 --> 00:06:45.361
And he needs the
right jury to do that.

150
00:06:45.405 --> 00:06:48.538
and he feels very strongly
that it should be us.

151
00:06:48.582 --> 00:06:50.322
I mean. me.

152
00:06:50.366 --> 00:06:52.542
Obviously. I wouldn't
want you involved in this.

153
00:06:52.586 --> 00:06:55.937
You're not seriously thinking
about helping him. are you?

154
00:06:55.980 --> 00:06:58.113
I agreed to it this morning.

155
00:06:58.156 --> 00:07:00.463
Oh. you did?

156
00:07:00.507 --> 00:07:03.814
Well. where does
that leave me. Bull?

157
00:07:03.858 --> 00:07:06.382
It leaves you six points
ahead in the D.A.'s race.

158
00:07:06.426 --> 00:07:08.036
Yeah. but the
second you announce

159
00:07:08.079 --> 00:07:09.385
that you're taking the case.

160
00:07:09.429 --> 00:07:11.256
the media's gonna come after me.

161
00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:13.563
They're gonna say. "Hey.
don't you still work at TAC?"

162
00:07:13.607 --> 00:07:16.261
"Are you saying that-that
Dave Sherman is innocent?

163
00:07:16.305 --> 00:07:18.699
"Are you saying that you
condone the corruption

164
00:07:18.742 --> 00:07:20.135
that led to him resigning?"

165
00:07:20.178 --> 00:07:21.702
I know it's tricky. Benny.

166
00:07:21.745 --> 00:07:22.983
but you and your team will
figure out something to say.

167
00:07:23.007 --> 00:07:24.966
That's your answer? Yes.

168
00:07:25.009 --> 00:07:27.403
That is my answer.

169
00:07:27.447 --> 00:07:30.493
Why are you doing this to me?

170
00:07:30.537 --> 00:07:34.105
[laughs] I'm not
doing this to you.

171
00:07:34.889 --> 00:07:37.108
You just got to trust me. Benny.

172
00:07:37.848 --> 00:07:40.634
Anyone else know?

173
00:07:40.677 --> 00:07:43.158
No. just you.

174
00:07:43.201 --> 00:07:45.421
I'd like to keep it that way.

175
00:07:51.166 --> 00:07:53.124
So let me get this straight.

176
00:07:53.168 --> 00:07:56.084
You stab me in the back.
and then you ask me

177
00:07:56.127 --> 00:07:58.390
to please keep it a secret.

178
00:08:00.175 --> 00:08:02.394
Whatever you say. Bull.

179
00:08:08.226 --> 00:08:10.490
♪

180
00:08:15.756 --> 00:08:19.542
In about two hours. there's
going to be a press announcement

181
00:08:19.586 --> 00:08:22.371
that David Sherman has
officially fired his counsel

182
00:08:22.414 --> 00:08:25.679
and hired TAC to represent him
against charges of corruption

183
00:08:25.722 --> 00:08:28.203
that have been leveled by
the State's Attorney General.

184
00:08:28.246 --> 00:08:30.945
Wait a second. David Sherman.
the dirty district attorney

185
00:08:30.988 --> 00:08:33.164
that Benny is
running to replace?

186
00:08:33.208 --> 00:08:36.472
For what it's worth. I
don't believe he's dirty.

187
00:08:36.516 --> 00:08:40.128
And I strongly believe
that he is innocent.

188
00:08:40.171 --> 00:08:41.564
I also believe he's my friend.

189
00:08:41.608 --> 00:08:45.133
And yeah. it's
that David Sherman.

190
00:08:45.176 --> 00:08:47.527
Isn't Benny also a friend?

191
00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:50.573
TAC is a business. and
Mr. Sherman needs our help.

192
00:08:50.617 --> 00:08:53.750
Mr. Palmer. you will be
our attorney of record.

193
00:08:53.794 --> 00:08:56.536
Okay. Okay. so
here's what happened.

194
00:08:56.579 --> 00:09:00.452
Two years ago. during
an afternoon of

195
00:09:00.496 --> 00:09:02.672
unusually blustery winds.
a construction crane

196
00:09:02.716 --> 00:09:05.196
in Midtown Manhattan toppled
over. killed a pedestrian

197
00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:06.589
on the street below.

198
00:09:06.633 --> 00:09:08.088
Now the owner of the
construction company

199
00:09:08.112 --> 00:09:10.680
that owned and operated
the crane in question

200
00:09:10.724 --> 00:09:13.117
was charged with
negligent homicide.

201
00:09:13.161 --> 00:09:14.597
And after he was charged.

202
00:09:14.641 --> 00:09:16.338
he paid a visit to
the D.A.'s office.

203
00:09:16.381 --> 00:09:18.122
The two men spoke at length.

204
00:09:18.166 --> 00:09:20.777
and shortly thereafter.
the charges were dropped.

205
00:09:20.821 --> 00:09:23.650
So wait. Is that why he's
being charged with corruption?

206
00:09:23.693 --> 00:09:25.216
No.

207
00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:28.611
The reason D.A. Sherman was
charged with corruption was that

208
00:09:28.655 --> 00:09:31.353
after the negligent
homicide charge was dropped.

209
00:09:31.396 --> 00:09:33.485
the attorney general
held a review

210
00:09:33.529 --> 00:09:35.575
of his campaign
finance accounts.

211
00:09:35.618 --> 00:09:37.707
And it turns out...
Would you believe it...

212
00:09:37.751 --> 00:09:41.015
Almost $100.000 worth of
campaign contributions suddenly

213
00:09:41.058 --> 00:09:43.931
appeared from the
construction company owner.

214
00:09:43.974 --> 00:09:46.194
from his employees.
from his relatives.

215
00:09:46.237 --> 00:09:48.022
even some of his neighbors.

216
00:09:48.065 --> 00:09:50.285
So the inference is the
construction company owner

217
00:09:50.328 --> 00:09:52.156
bought his way out
of the conviction?

218
00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:53.636
Yeah. but the guy resigned.

219
00:09:53.680 --> 00:09:56.117
He didn't even fight
it. He just... resigned.

220
00:09:56.160 --> 00:09:59.642
No. He resigned so
he couldfight it.

221
00:09:59.686 --> 00:10:02.253
Unfortunately. most of the
public doesn't see it that way.

222
00:10:02.297 --> 00:10:05.822
which is where we come in.

223
00:10:05.866 --> 00:10:07.084
Yes. Ms. Rentzel.

224
00:10:07.128 --> 00:10:08.520
Is it okay to ask

225
00:10:08.564 --> 00:10:10.740
how Benny feels about all this?

226
00:10:10.784 --> 00:10:13.525
Well. I'm sure he is surprised.

227
00:10:13.569 --> 00:10:15.702
I'm sure he's somewhat hurt.

228
00:10:15.745 --> 00:10:18.618
You should feel free to ask him.

229
00:10:22.534 --> 00:10:24.449
What can I do to help?

230
00:10:25.625 --> 00:10:27.714
Are you talking to me?

231
00:10:27.757 --> 00:10:31.021
The man who betrayed the most
likable man in the world?

232
00:10:31.065 --> 00:10:32.893
It's my job to help.

233
00:10:32.936 --> 00:10:36.984
Thank you. I guess we need
to find out everything we can

234
00:10:37.027 --> 00:10:38.246
about this attorney general.

235
00:10:38.289 --> 00:10:39.527
He's the one who
brought the charges

236
00:10:39.551 --> 00:10:40.833
against our client.
I'd love to know why.

237
00:10:40.857 --> 00:10:42.467
Sounds like a job for Danny.

238
00:10:42.511 --> 00:10:44.489
I'd love to get a look at
Sherman's campaign records.

239
00:10:44.513 --> 00:10:45.873
I want to know the
name of everyone

240
00:10:45.906 --> 00:10:49.474
that gave even a dime
to get him elected.

241
00:10:51.346 --> 00:10:54.349
BULL: Look.
everything I am doing

242
00:10:54.392 --> 00:10:57.831
I promise you I am doing because
I care about your brother.

243
00:10:57.874 --> 00:10:59.504
You know. just because
the man comes to you.

244
00:10:59.528 --> 00:11:03.706
just because the man needs
you... you can still say "no."

245
00:11:03.750 --> 00:11:07.101
Okay. it is a little bit
more complicated than that.

246
00:11:07.144 --> 00:11:09.470
And I wish it were simple and
I could just explain it to you.

247
00:11:09.494 --> 00:11:11.105
but I can't.

248
00:11:11.888 --> 00:11:13.890
Tell me why it isn't.

249
00:11:14.195 --> 00:11:15.196
I can't.

250
00:11:15.239 --> 00:11:16.937
You just have to trust me.

251
00:11:19.374 --> 00:11:22.203
I think we should put this
wedding thing on hold.

252
00:11:22.246 --> 00:11:26.468
I mean. it's not a threat.
it's just... with the election

253
00:11:26.511 --> 00:11:28.644
and-and COVID's not
even completely over

254
00:11:28.688 --> 00:11:30.733
and then now this?

255
00:11:30.777 --> 00:11:32.648
It just... [exhales]

256
00:11:32.692 --> 00:11:34.128
It all feels like a sign.

257
00:11:34.171 --> 00:11:36.391
like-like the world's
trying to tell us something

258
00:11:36.434 --> 00:11:39.394
or just trying to tell
me something. anyway.

259
00:11:40.700 --> 00:11:42.179
[crowd clamoring]

260
00:11:42.223 --> 00:11:43.790
BENNY: Okay.
everybody. everybody.

261
00:11:43.833 --> 00:11:46.009
please. please. please.

262
00:11:46.053 --> 00:11:48.533
I know what you are
all here to ask me.

263
00:11:48.577 --> 00:11:51.754
Okay? And just like you.
I found out this morning

264
00:11:51.798 --> 00:11:54.365
that former District
Attorney Sherman has hired

265
00:11:54.409 --> 00:11:57.281
the Trial Analysis
Corporation to represent him

266
00:11:57.325 --> 00:12:00.415
in his upcoming court fight
against the State of New York.

267
00:12:00.458 --> 00:12:04.071
So that there is no ambiguity
about my relationship

268
00:12:04.114 --> 00:12:05.855
with regard to Mr. Sherman.

269
00:12:05.899 --> 00:12:09.990
I am hereby announcing that
I. from this moment forward.

270
00:12:10.033 --> 00:12:14.603
choose not to be employed by
the Trial Analysis Corporation.

271
00:12:14.646 --> 00:12:18.694
in any capacity. and have
offered my resignation

272
00:12:18.738 --> 00:12:21.436
via notarized letter.

273
00:12:21.479 --> 00:12:24.656
Good to see you all. and
thank you for listening.

274
00:12:24.700 --> 00:12:26.049
[reporters clamoring]

275
00:12:27.834 --> 00:12:30.575
[phone ringing]

276
00:12:30.619 --> 00:12:32.229
Hmm?

277
00:12:34.492 --> 00:12:35.711
Hey.

278
00:12:35.755 --> 00:12:38.105
BULL: Did I wake you?

279
00:12:38.148 --> 00:12:41.064
No. Where are you?

280
00:12:41.108 --> 00:12:42.500
The office.

281
00:12:42.544 --> 00:12:45.025
Will probably
sleep here tonight.

282
00:12:46.853 --> 00:12:49.681
You don't have to. uh.
put up such a fuss.

283
00:12:50.770 --> 00:12:52.815
I didn't tell you
not to come home.

284
00:12:52.859 --> 00:12:54.817
No. I know. [Sighs]

285
00:12:55.818 --> 00:12:57.298
How's the candidate?

286
00:12:58.212 --> 00:13:02.172
Well. he seems kind
of bulletproof.

287
00:13:02.216 --> 00:13:03.652
He made his announcement today

288
00:13:03.695 --> 00:13:06.568
and his numbers went up
a point in the polls.

289
00:13:06.611 --> 00:13:09.049
Ah. well. you can
thank me later.

290
00:13:11.007 --> 00:13:12.530
How's the case?

291
00:13:13.401 --> 00:13:15.795
Pretty bullet-riddled. actually.

292
00:13:17.187 --> 00:13:18.580
Tell me there'll be a day

293
00:13:18.623 --> 00:13:20.277
that I'll actually
understand all of this.

294
00:13:20.321 --> 00:13:21.801
I swear to you
there will be a day

295
00:13:21.844 --> 00:13:24.107
when you actually
understand all of this.

296
00:13:24.151 --> 00:13:26.631
I'm holding you to that.

297
00:13:26.675 --> 00:13:29.852
So I heard from some
people around the office

298
00:13:29.896 --> 00:13:32.550
that my Saturday
just got freed up.

299
00:13:32.594 --> 00:13:34.726
I seem to remember that. uh.

300
00:13:34.770 --> 00:13:37.338
there was some kind of
event on the calendar.

301
00:13:41.821 --> 00:13:43.953
[exhales]

302
00:13:43.997 --> 00:13:46.695
It was called on
account of rain.

303
00:13:46.738 --> 00:13:48.871
Aha.

304
00:13:48.915 --> 00:13:50.873
Well. what's your best guess?

305
00:13:50.917 --> 00:13:54.094
Will we be playing a
makeup game someday

306
00:13:54.137 --> 00:13:56.009
when the sun comes back out?

307
00:13:56.836 --> 00:13:59.316
Let's just get through
the rain first.

308
00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:01.797
Okay.

309
00:14:03.190 --> 00:14:04.408
Talk tomorrow.

310
00:14:04.452 --> 00:14:06.410
Talk tomorrow.

311
00:14:10.153 --> 00:14:11.153
[sighs]

312
00:14:18.858 --> 00:14:20.947
Jack Martel. You ever
heard of this guy?

313
00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:23.340
No. sounds like
a game show host.

314
00:14:23.384 --> 00:14:24.864
Taylor. Yo.

315
00:14:24.907 --> 00:14:26.822
I got emailed the
revised witness list

316
00:14:26.866 --> 00:14:28.389
very early this morning.

317
00:14:28.432 --> 00:14:31.000
The name at the top of
it is "Jack Martel."

318
00:14:31.044 --> 00:14:32.872
M-A-R-T-E-L.

319
00:14:32.915 --> 00:14:33.829
[elevator bell chimes]

320
00:14:33.873 --> 00:14:35.657
Hey. So what do you know?

321
00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:38.616
TAYLOR: Well. assuming Jack is
actually Jonathan... no "H"...

322
00:14:38.660 --> 00:14:40.923
He seems to be a
professional investigator

323
00:14:40.967 --> 00:14:43.404
who actually worked for our
client for almost four years.

324
00:14:43.447 --> 00:14:46.189
but then left him to go
work for... wait for it...

325
00:14:46.233 --> 00:14:47.799
The attorney general.

326
00:14:47.843 --> 00:14:49.236
And when did this happen?

327
00:14:49.279 --> 00:14:50.977
Almost two years ago.
Right around the time

328
00:14:51.020 --> 00:14:53.936
the A.G. announced he was
considering a run for Senate.

329
00:14:59.072 --> 00:15:01.291
[quietly]: So. Jack Martel
used to work for you?

330
00:15:01.335 --> 00:15:03.598
Yeah. Why you ask?

331
00:15:03.641 --> 00:15:05.600
He's the first witness
up this morning.

332
00:15:05.643 --> 00:15:08.037
BULL: Any idea
why he jumped ship

333
00:15:08.081 --> 00:15:10.431
and went to the attorney
general's office?

334
00:15:10.474 --> 00:15:13.913
Well. he... he
never said as much.

335
00:15:13.956 --> 00:15:16.872
but the A.G. was making
noise about a Senate run.

336
00:15:16.916 --> 00:15:18.830
and I was letting it
be known that I thought

337
00:15:18.874 --> 00:15:20.484
I was the man for that job.

338
00:15:20.528 --> 00:15:22.791
and I think Martel
voted with his feet.

339
00:15:22.834 --> 00:15:25.141
Nothing like loyalty.

340
00:15:25.185 --> 00:15:27.622
My name is Jack Martel.
I'm an investigator

341
00:15:27.665 --> 00:15:29.624
for the New York Attorney
General's Office.

342
00:15:29.667 --> 00:15:31.626
And how did you
come to be involved

343
00:15:31.669 --> 00:15:33.367
with the matter before
the court today?

344
00:15:33.410 --> 00:15:36.065
Little less than two years
ago. a Manhattan contractor

345
00:15:36.109 --> 00:15:39.286
named Dean Burroughs was working
on a construction project

346
00:15:39.329 --> 00:15:42.811
on the West Side of Manhattan
when one of his cranes.

347
00:15:42.854 --> 00:15:45.683
which was over 40 stories
in the air. collapsed.

348
00:15:45.727 --> 00:15:47.990
killing a man on
the street below.

349
00:15:48.034 --> 00:15:50.862
It was announced that
Mr. Burroughs. the contractor.

350
00:15:50.906 --> 00:15:53.996
was being charged with
negligent homicide.

351
00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:56.781
and then. a short time
later. it was announced

352
00:15:56.825 --> 00:15:58.914
that the charges were dropped.

353
00:15:58.958 --> 00:16:01.656
No real explanation.
just dropped.

354
00:16:01.699 --> 00:16:04.876
That's when my boss's
phone started ringing.

355
00:16:04.920 --> 00:16:06.028
And as you explained previously.

356
00:16:06.052 --> 00:16:08.010
your boss is the
attorney general.

357
00:16:08.054 --> 00:16:09.533
That's right. That's correct.

358
00:16:09.577 --> 00:16:11.100
What did you discover?

359
00:16:11.144 --> 00:16:15.322
I discovered that after
Mr. Burroughs was arrested.

360
00:16:15.365 --> 00:16:18.020
he requested and was
given an opportunity

361
00:16:18.064 --> 00:16:21.763
to meet with then District
Attorney Mr. Sherman.

362
00:16:22.633 --> 00:16:24.635
And what was the
purpose of that meeting?

363
00:16:24.679 --> 00:16:27.769
Mr. Burroughs asked
him to dismiss

364
00:16:27.812 --> 00:16:30.032
the homicide
charges against him.

365
00:16:30.076 --> 00:16:32.817
And did the defendant
dismiss the charges

366
00:16:32.861 --> 00:16:33.993
against Mr. Burroughs?

367
00:16:34.036 --> 00:16:37.039
Eight days after their meeting.

368
00:16:37.083 --> 00:16:38.867
WEST: And then
what happened next?

369
00:16:38.910 --> 00:16:41.522
We took a shot in the dark.

370
00:16:41.565 --> 00:16:43.002
We did a forensic accounting

371
00:16:43.045 --> 00:16:45.656
of Mr. Sherman's
campaign finances.

372
00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:48.181
and we discovered that
in the weeks and months

373
00:16:48.224 --> 00:16:50.966
following the
dismissal. Mr. Burroughs

374
00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:53.925
gave $10.000 to
Mr. Sherman's campaign.

375
00:16:53.969 --> 00:16:57.625
His wife contributed
another six.

376
00:16:57.668 --> 00:17:01.063
His father contributed
another $12.000

377
00:17:01.107 --> 00:17:02.586
and his brother
and sister-in-law

378
00:17:02.630 --> 00:17:04.893
each contributed 13.

379
00:17:04.936 --> 00:17:06.938
And their total contributions?

380
00:17:06.982 --> 00:17:08.331
$54.000.

381
00:17:08.375 --> 00:17:10.638
And in addition. another $45.000

382
00:17:10.681 --> 00:17:14.120
that was traced back
to friends. neighbors

383
00:17:14.163 --> 00:17:17.384
and employees of
Mr. Burroughs's business.

384
00:17:17.427 --> 00:17:21.083
A total of roughly $100.000.

385
00:17:21.127 --> 00:17:23.216
Did you ask Mr. Sherman
about the money?

386
00:17:23.259 --> 00:17:26.175
Of course. I remember
what he said to me.

387
00:17:26.219 --> 00:17:30.614
"You know how these things work.
One hand washes the other."

388
00:17:32.007 --> 00:17:34.879
And then he said.
"$100.000 actually gets you

389
00:17:34.923 --> 00:17:36.881
a pretty good scrub."
[laughs softly]

390
00:17:39.406 --> 00:17:40.494
WEST: Thank you.

391
00:17:40.537 --> 00:17:42.887
No further questions.

392
00:17:48.154 --> 00:17:49.416
CHUNK: Morning. Mr. Martel.

393
00:17:49.459 --> 00:17:50.634
Good morning.

394
00:17:50.678 --> 00:17:53.115
So. let me make sure
that I understand.

395
00:17:53.159 --> 00:17:55.248
You expect this jury to believe

396
00:17:55.291 --> 00:17:57.119
that the district
attorney of Manhattan.

397
00:17:57.163 --> 00:18:00.296
a man who's raised millions of
dollars in campaign donations.

398
00:18:00.340 --> 00:18:04.909
would be willing to throw
it all away for $100.000?

399
00:18:04.953 --> 00:18:06.148
[scoffs] I'm just
telling you what I know.

400
00:18:06.172 --> 00:18:07.869
I'm telling you
what he... A-And...

401
00:18:07.912 --> 00:18:11.046
And after he supposedly
put his reputation

402
00:18:11.090 --> 00:18:14.093
and his career and his
livelihood on the line.

403
00:18:14.136 --> 00:18:16.486
that he would brag about it?

404
00:18:16.530 --> 00:18:18.140
To you?

405
00:18:18.184 --> 00:18:21.839
A man who quit working
for him with no notice?

406
00:18:23.624 --> 00:18:24.862
That's what you're
telling the jury?

407
00:18:24.886 --> 00:18:27.236
Objection. Badgering.

408
00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:28.846
Sustained.

409
00:18:28.890 --> 00:18:30.979
Let me ask you another question.

410
00:18:31.022 --> 00:18:33.634
Did you conduct an
independent investigation

411
00:18:33.677 --> 00:18:35.288
of the crane accident?

412
00:18:35.331 --> 00:18:36.158
I did.

413
00:18:36.202 --> 00:18:38.595
Negligent homicide requires

414
00:18:38.639 --> 00:18:42.512
proof that Burroughs' actions
caused the death of the victim.

415
00:18:42.556 --> 00:18:45.950
Isn't it entirely reasonable
that my client determined

416
00:18:45.994 --> 00:18:50.085
that those facts did not
satisfy that burden of proof?

417
00:18:50.129 --> 00:18:51.956
All I can tell you is
he was more than happy

418
00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.176
to share with me that
his campaign pocketed

419
00:18:54.220 --> 00:18:57.875
a lot of money in the
aftermath of that decision.

420
00:18:58.702 --> 00:19:00.400
Mm... You didn't record it?

421
00:19:04.969 --> 00:19:06.928
You didn't record it?

422
00:19:07.711 --> 00:19:08.973
Nope.

423
00:19:09.017 --> 00:19:11.541
And there were no
other witnesses?

424
00:19:11.585 --> 00:19:13.195
Nope.

425
00:19:13.239 --> 00:19:16.198
Well. it makes sense. you worked
for the man for a long time.

426
00:19:16.242 --> 00:19:18.766
and clearly you two
knew each other well.

427
00:19:18.809 --> 00:19:23.162
and safe to say that he'd
trust you with his secrets?

428
00:19:23.205 --> 00:19:25.294
He obviously did.

429
00:19:25.338 --> 00:19:27.688
So can you tell us another?

430
00:19:27.731 --> 00:19:30.081
Excuse me? Tell
me another secret.

431
00:19:30.125 --> 00:19:32.910
Tell me another time. in all the
time that you worked with him.

432
00:19:32.954 --> 00:19:35.304
that he broke the law.

433
00:19:35.348 --> 00:19:37.219
betrayed his oath of office.

434
00:19:37.263 --> 00:19:38.655
betrayed the trust of the people

435
00:19:38.699 --> 00:19:42.485
that put him in that
office multiple times.

436
00:19:42.529 --> 00:19:44.705
Mr. Martel.

437
00:19:44.748 --> 00:19:47.751
you just testified under oath
that District Attorney Sherman

438
00:19:47.795 --> 00:19:50.363
was willing to let a
guilty man go scot-free

439
00:19:50.406 --> 00:19:53.017
for the right price.

440
00:19:53.061 --> 00:19:55.716
Now. are you trying
to convince this jury

441
00:19:55.759 --> 00:19:57.519
that in all the time
that you worked for him.

442
00:19:57.544 --> 00:20:01.591
that you never saw him commit
any other illegal acts?

443
00:20:03.419 --> 00:20:06.379
I'm waiting for an answer. sir.

444
00:20:07.554 --> 00:20:09.599
Not off the top of my head.

445
00:20:09.643 --> 00:20:11.079
Bingo.

446
00:20:11.122 --> 00:20:12.522
Well. if any other
part of your head

447
00:20:12.559 --> 00:20:15.214
comes up with another
answer. don't be shy.

448
00:20:15.257 --> 00:20:16.911
Feel free to let us know.

449
00:20:16.954 --> 00:20:19.783
Now. let me ask you this.

450
00:20:19.827 --> 00:20:22.743
Are you aware that
the attorney general.

451
00:20:22.786 --> 00:20:25.572
the prosecutor's
boss... And your boss...

452
00:20:25.615 --> 00:20:27.443
Is eyeing a run for the Senate?

453
00:20:27.487 --> 00:20:29.576
Objection! Relevance?
Your Honor...

454
00:20:29.619 --> 00:20:32.361
This cuts to the very core
of our defense. Your Honor.

455
00:20:32.405 --> 00:20:34.450
as this is obviously a
politically-motivated

456
00:20:34.494 --> 00:20:36.713
persecution of an innocent man

457
00:20:36.757 --> 00:20:40.456
who happens to be
contemplating the same seat.

458
00:20:40.500 --> 00:20:42.719
BULL: You see how he snuck
that motive in there?

459
00:20:42.763 --> 00:20:46.288
No question. no witness.
Think someone might object?

460
00:20:46.332 --> 00:20:48.725
Objection. Counsel
is testifying.

461
00:20:48.769 --> 00:20:52.294
Enough. You know better
than that. Mr. Palmer.

462
00:20:52.338 --> 00:20:53.904
He sure does. Thank goodness.

463
00:20:53.948 --> 00:20:55.558
I'm sorry. Your Honor.

464
00:20:55.602 --> 00:20:58.431
But I submit that the attorney
general's political ambitions

465
00:20:58.474 --> 00:21:03.087
are wholly relevant to show
his bias towards Mr. Sherman.

466
00:21:03.131 --> 00:21:06.787
He pulled a Britney Spears
there. Oops. he did it again.

467
00:21:07.657 --> 00:21:09.877
Ms. West. the man makes a point.

468
00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:11.052
Fine.

469
00:21:11.095 --> 00:21:13.010
Let the record show

470
00:21:13.054 --> 00:21:14.934
that we stipulate the
attorney general has filed

471
00:21:14.969 --> 00:21:17.319
the requisite papers
for a Senate run.

472
00:21:17.363 --> 00:21:18.581
Stipulation noted.

473
00:21:18.625 --> 00:21:20.931
Any further
questions. Counselor?

474
00:21:20.975 --> 00:21:24.021
Nope. Not a one.

475
00:21:27.111 --> 00:21:29.853
True confession?

476
00:21:29.897 --> 00:21:31.942
For the first time today.

477
00:21:31.986 --> 00:21:34.380
I thought. "Bull's been
right about this all along."

478
00:21:34.423 --> 00:21:35.729
"Man's innocent.

479
00:21:35.772 --> 00:21:37.252
"Of course he had
to take this case.

480
00:21:37.296 --> 00:21:39.012
"Of course he wouldn't
allow that man to go to jail

481
00:21:39.036 --> 00:21:41.014
"for something that's
becoming more and more obvious

482
00:21:41.038 --> 00:21:44.738
"that he did not do." [chuckles]

483
00:21:44.781 --> 00:21:46.783
You might want to reserve
judgement on all that.

484
00:21:48.002 --> 00:21:50.483
What. are you saying
he isn't innocent?

485
00:21:50.526 --> 00:21:53.312
I'm saying maybe
I'm not so smart.

486
00:21:53.355 --> 00:21:55.705
Maybe not so steeped in virtue.

487
00:21:55.749 --> 00:21:58.752
Oh. come on. Bull. You
upset a lot of people.

488
00:21:58.795 --> 00:22:00.295
You destroyed an
important relationship.

489
00:22:00.319 --> 00:22:02.712
You... you were supposed to
get married this weekend.

490
00:22:02.756 --> 00:22:04.888
And I admire how you didn't

491
00:22:04.932 --> 00:22:07.587
let anything or anyone
compromise your principles.

492
00:22:07.630 --> 00:22:09.763
That's something. man.

493
00:22:09.806 --> 00:22:12.156
I had a gun to my head.

494
00:22:17.510 --> 00:22:19.338
[sighs]

495
00:22:19.381 --> 00:22:21.252
What's this for?

496
00:22:22.471 --> 00:22:24.865
I just hired you.

497
00:22:24.908 --> 00:22:28.651
And now I would like to invoke
attorney-client privilege.

498
00:22:32.786 --> 00:22:34.614
About eight or so years ago.

499
00:22:34.657 --> 00:22:36.703
maybe the third case
Benny and I ever had.

500
00:22:36.746 --> 00:22:39.009
this anesthesiologist
calls us out of the blue.

501
00:22:39.053 --> 00:22:41.447
Nice guy. Terrible story.

502
00:22:41.490 --> 00:22:44.798
His wife and child
had been killed

503
00:22:44.841 --> 00:22:47.278
in what looked like a
horrific murder-suicide.

504
00:22:47.322 --> 00:22:50.194
The mother had...
suffocated the baby

505
00:22:50.238 --> 00:22:52.240
and then shot herself.

506
00:22:53.067 --> 00:22:54.808
But as the investigation
went along.

507
00:22:54.851 --> 00:22:57.811
the detectives started
to think... otherwise.

508
00:22:57.854 --> 00:22:59.900
They started to think the
whole thing looked staged.

509
00:22:59.943 --> 00:23:03.469
And that this anesthesiologist
had killed his family.

510
00:23:03.512 --> 00:23:06.646
So... Benny and I
got down to business.

511
00:23:06.689 --> 00:23:08.648
We did our thing...
You've seen it.

512
00:23:08.691 --> 00:23:09.910
Benny can dance.

513
00:23:09.953 --> 00:23:11.825
I mean. he got out
there... [laugh]

514
00:23:11.868 --> 00:23:13.827
Watching him in court

515
00:23:13.870 --> 00:23:15.437
took my breath away.

516
00:23:15.481 --> 00:23:18.397
And four weeks and a hell
of a closing argument later

517
00:23:19.310 --> 00:23:21.530
the jury voted not guilty.

518
00:23:21.574 --> 00:23:22.923
All right. Benny.

519
00:23:22.966 --> 00:23:24.490
Mm-hmm.

520
00:23:25.404 --> 00:23:28.842
Yeah. so Benny and his
client went out to celebrate.

521
00:23:28.885 --> 00:23:30.670
And sometime after midnight.

522
00:23:30.713 --> 00:23:32.976
after having more drinks
than Benny could count.

523
00:23:33.020 --> 00:23:35.326
our client confessed
to his attorney

524
00:23:35.370 --> 00:23:37.503
that he actually did it.

525
00:23:37.546 --> 00:23:39.374
That he did kill his family.

526
00:23:39.418 --> 00:23:41.420
And now. thanks to Benny
and my combined skills.

527
00:23:41.463 --> 00:23:44.684
he was gonna have the
life he really wanted.

528
00:23:44.727 --> 00:23:46.816
Oh. my...

529
00:23:46.860 --> 00:23:48.035
What did you do?

530
00:23:48.078 --> 00:23:49.210
I didn't do anything.

531
00:23:49.253 --> 00:23:50.666
But Benny beat the
crap out of the guy.

532
00:23:50.690 --> 00:23:52.256
Knocked out two
teeth. broke a rib.

533
00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:53.606
Gave him a concussion.

534
00:23:53.649 --> 00:23:55.869
That's called
assault. by the way.

535
00:23:55.912 --> 00:23:57.218
You go to jail for that.

536
00:23:57.261 --> 00:23:59.786
Lose your license
to practice law.

537
00:23:59.829 --> 00:24:01.744
for that.

538
00:24:03.267 --> 00:24:05.052
Benny was. understandably.
in a panic.

539
00:24:05.095 --> 00:24:07.117
And I kept telling him he didn't
have anything to worry about.

540
00:24:07.141 --> 00:24:09.404
A man who just got away
with murder is not gonna run

541
00:24:09.448 --> 00:24:11.711
to the cops 'cause somebody
messed up his smile.

542
00:24:11.754 --> 00:24:13.234
Yeah...

543
00:24:13.277 --> 00:24:15.062
I was wrong.

544
00:24:15.105 --> 00:24:17.543
The anesthesiologist
filed charges.

545
00:24:17.586 --> 00:24:19.632
Oh. no.

546
00:24:20.763 --> 00:24:22.809
So I went to the D.A.

547
00:24:22.852 --> 00:24:24.550
Unbeknownst to Benny.

548
00:24:24.593 --> 00:24:26.247
Our client.

549
00:24:26.290 --> 00:24:28.075
Mr. Sherman.

550
00:24:28.118 --> 00:24:29.555
The most honest
man in the world.

551
00:24:29.598 --> 00:24:32.558
Never bent a rule.
never broke a law.

552
00:24:33.559 --> 00:24:36.039
But now it was my turn.

553
00:24:36.083 --> 00:24:39.260
And I danced and I pleaded
and I did everything I could.

554
00:24:39.303 --> 00:24:42.263
And finally D.A. Sherman got it.

555
00:24:43.090 --> 00:24:45.658
'Cause he knew Benny. he
knew he was a good man.

556
00:24:45.701 --> 00:24:47.790
Yeah. Knew he had a good heart.

557
00:24:48.965 --> 00:24:51.228
So he took the
murderer's complaint

558
00:24:51.272 --> 00:24:54.318
and D.A. Sherman
conveniently just lost it.

559
00:24:54.362 --> 00:24:56.538
It just disappeared.

560
00:24:56.582 --> 00:25:00.281
And to Benny. it seemed like
the whole thing just blew over.

561
00:25:01.064 --> 00:25:03.240
Well

562
00:25:03.284 --> 00:25:05.765
that's n-nice. I guess.

563
00:25:05.808 --> 00:25:08.768
And then. as luck would have
it. our anesthesiologist friend

564
00:25:08.811 --> 00:25:11.205
had a little party with
himself and some amyl nitrate

565
00:25:11.248 --> 00:25:12.989
and ended up choking
on his own vomit.

566
00:25:13.033 --> 00:25:16.602
Well. sounds like. uh.
it was all meant to be.

567
00:25:16.645 --> 00:25:18.429
Sounds like it.

568
00:25:18.473 --> 00:25:21.737
Did I mention that I told
the D.A. I owed him one?

569
00:25:22.869 --> 00:25:25.306
And that. by the way.
what the D.A. and I did.

570
00:25:25.349 --> 00:25:26.655
that

571
00:25:26.699 --> 00:25:28.788
is called obstruction
of justice.

572
00:25:28.831 --> 00:25:32.182
And for that. they lock you
up and throw away the key.

573
00:25:36.230 --> 00:25:37.405
Okay.

574
00:25:43.237 --> 00:25:46.806
[whoops] I am up one
point in the polls.

575
00:25:46.849 --> 00:25:49.983
So. you hear anything
about the trial?

576
00:25:50.026 --> 00:25:52.594
Whole thing's pretty much
a foregone conclusion.

577
00:25:52.638 --> 00:25:56.467
Lots of muscle on one side.
almost none on Sherman's.

578
00:25:57.425 --> 00:25:59.645
Hey. Don't underestimate TAC.

579
00:25:59.688 --> 00:26:03.170
Don't underestimate the will
of the attorney general.

580
00:26:03.953 --> 00:26:05.607
Look. I don't know if
Sherman actually did

581
00:26:05.651 --> 00:26:07.000
the things they're claiming.

582
00:26:07.043 --> 00:26:09.045
I just know. as someone
who worked for him.

583
00:26:09.089 --> 00:26:12.048
the guy made it impossible for
people like me to get ahead.

584
00:26:12.092 --> 00:26:13.615
Held his staff

585
00:26:13.659 --> 00:26:15.617
to an impossible standard.

586
00:26:15.661 --> 00:26:17.837
I don't know. I mean. I

587
00:26:17.880 --> 00:26:20.709
just always saw him
as a straight shooter.

588
00:26:20.753 --> 00:26:22.102
An idealist.

589
00:26:22.145 --> 00:26:23.364
You know? There's

590
00:26:23.407 --> 00:26:24.844
nothing wrong with that.

591
00:26:24.887 --> 00:26:27.542
There is if you're trying
to get things done.

592
00:26:27.586 --> 00:26:30.414
For the people and for yourself.

593
00:26:34.549 --> 00:26:36.072
Oh. come on. Benny.

594
00:26:36.116 --> 00:26:38.597
Nobody who's any good at
the business of government

595
00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:39.772
is completely straight.

596
00:26:39.815 --> 00:26:40.903
You can't be.

597
00:26:40.947 --> 00:26:43.645
There's too much
money changing hands.

598
00:26:43.689 --> 00:26:45.168
Anybody who's smart is planning

599
00:26:45.212 --> 00:26:47.475
their exit strategy and
their retirement package

600
00:26:47.518 --> 00:26:49.042
from the moment
they get in there.

601
00:26:49.085 --> 00:26:50.434
They have to.

602
00:26:50.478 --> 00:26:52.915
That's why a-a guy
like Sherman had to go.

603
00:26:52.959 --> 00:26:55.265
[exhales] He stands in the
way of too many things.

604
00:26:55.309 --> 00:26:56.571
too many people.

605
00:26:56.615 --> 00:26:58.878
too much money.

606
00:26:58.921 --> 00:27:01.315
It'll be different when you
and I are running things.

607
00:27:02.751 --> 00:27:04.207
SHERMAN: When I first heard
about the indictments.

608
00:27:04.231 --> 00:27:06.625
I was stunned.

609
00:27:06.668 --> 00:27:09.410
I had been district attorney
of Manhattan for over a decade

610
00:27:09.453 --> 00:27:12.413
and always prided myself
on being above reproach.

611
00:27:12.456 --> 00:27:14.284
CHUNK: Then why resign?

612
00:27:14.328 --> 00:27:15.895
Why not stick it out and fight?

613
00:27:15.938 --> 00:27:19.681
I had a strong feeling about
who it was I was up against.

614
00:27:19.725 --> 00:27:22.075
I knew it was gonna be a
long and difficult fight.

615
00:27:22.118 --> 00:27:24.164
one that was gonna demand
all of my attention.

616
00:27:24.207 --> 00:27:25.513
and I

617
00:27:25.556 --> 00:27:27.689
felt that the people of New York

618
00:27:27.733 --> 00:27:30.431
deserved better than
a part-time D.A.

619
00:27:30.474 --> 00:27:33.564
Well. let's talk about
this meeting that you had

620
00:27:33.608 --> 00:27:36.350
with the contractor.
Dean Burroughs.

621
00:27:36.393 --> 00:27:39.701
You see now how
having such a meeting

622
00:27:39.745 --> 00:27:42.138
might have given the
appearance of impropriety?

623
00:27:42.182 --> 00:27:44.053
Actually. I don't.

624
00:27:44.097 --> 00:27:46.708
Uh. Mr. Burroughs
was a constituent.

625
00:27:46.752 --> 00:27:48.536
I effectively worked for him.

626
00:27:48.579 --> 00:27:50.799
just as I do for
every other citizen.

627
00:27:50.843 --> 00:27:53.323
He hadn't yet been found
guilty of anything.

628
00:27:53.367 --> 00:27:56.283
So. looking back. you

629
00:27:56.326 --> 00:27:58.328
you don't regret
taking that meeting?

630
00:27:58.372 --> 00:28:01.157
No. I don't regret
taking the meeting.

631
00:28:01.201 --> 00:28:03.072
I believe it was
my responsibility

632
00:28:03.116 --> 00:28:04.465
to take that meeting.

633
00:28:04.508 --> 00:28:06.510
So. with regard to
this crane accident.

634
00:28:06.554 --> 00:28:09.818
did you ever meet with anyone
else other than Dean Burroughs.

635
00:28:09.862 --> 00:28:12.473
the man who was accused
of negligent homicide?

636
00:28:12.516 --> 00:28:15.258
Yes. I had a meeting
with Charlotte Morris.

637
00:28:15.302 --> 00:28:17.521
the widow of the man who
died when the crane fell.

638
00:28:18.392 --> 00:28:21.700
And did Mrs. Morris express
any opinion about the case?

639
00:28:21.743 --> 00:28:24.833
She believed what happened
was a tragic accident.

640
00:28:24.877 --> 00:28:27.836
She didn't want to
see any charges filed.

641
00:28:27.880 --> 00:28:30.534
Mr. Burroughs had already
agreed to a sizable

642
00:28:30.578 --> 00:28:32.667
multimillion-dollar
civil settlement.

643
00:28:32.711 --> 00:28:35.801
and Mrs. Morris felt that was
a satisfactory resolution.

644
00:28:35.844 --> 00:28:38.717
She said the family had
been through enough pain

645
00:28:38.760 --> 00:28:41.110
and they needed to move
on with their lives.

646
00:28:41.154 --> 00:28:42.546
you know. start to heal.

647
00:28:42.590 --> 00:28:44.723
And I agreed to allow her that.

648
00:28:44.766 --> 00:28:46.550
You know. everyone
keeps forgetting.

649
00:28:46.594 --> 00:28:50.511
this crane didn't just
fall out of the sky.

650
00:28:50.554 --> 00:28:52.774
We were in the middle
of a wind event

651
00:28:52.818 --> 00:28:56.778
with gusts that. at times.
topped 90 miles an hour.

652
00:28:56.822 --> 00:28:58.562
And the last time that
happened in this city

653
00:28:58.606 --> 00:29:00.086
was back in the 1960s.

654
00:29:00.129 --> 00:29:03.306
And I think Mrs. Morris
was very mindful of that.

655
00:29:03.350 --> 00:29:04.307
She viewed it

656
00:29:04.351 --> 00:29:05.831
as an act of God.

657
00:29:05.874 --> 00:29:08.398
as did the insurance company.

658
00:29:08.442 --> 00:29:10.096
As did I.

659
00:29:10.139 --> 00:29:12.552
The only one who appears not to
have embraced that point of view

660
00:29:12.576 --> 00:29:14.013
is the attorney general.

661
00:29:14.056 --> 00:29:16.580
I have no further
questions. Your Honor.

662
00:29:16.624 --> 00:29:20.149
Then court is adjourned
until 9:00 a.m. tomorrow.

663
00:29:20.193 --> 00:29:21.760
BULL: As the people
who've been with me

664
00:29:21.803 --> 00:29:23.215
the longest. I'm sure
you found my actions

665
00:29:23.239 --> 00:29:26.286
over the past week a
little puzzling. maybe

666
00:29:26.329 --> 00:29:27.853
even disappointing.

667
00:29:27.896 --> 00:29:29.376
And now.

668
00:29:29.419 --> 00:29:31.204
here we are. deep
enough into the trial

669
00:29:31.247 --> 00:29:34.250
for any reasonable
person to suspect that we

670
00:29:34.294 --> 00:29:35.904
will not prevail.

671
00:29:35.948 --> 00:29:38.820
So. I just wanted to thank
you all for your hard work

672
00:29:38.864 --> 00:29:41.301
and apologize if I let you down.

673
00:29:43.956 --> 00:29:46.045
For what it's worth.

674
00:29:46.088 --> 00:29:48.656
from what I have heard in court

675
00:29:48.699 --> 00:29:50.701
yesterday and today.

676
00:29:50.745 --> 00:29:53.530
it sounds to me like you
guys were punching holes

677
00:29:53.574 --> 00:29:55.706
in the other side's arguments.

678
00:29:55.750 --> 00:29:57.839
It's gonna take more than holes.

679
00:29:57.883 --> 00:30:00.711
[inhales] We need a
unanimous not guilty vote.

680
00:30:00.755 --> 00:30:02.080
or else we are
looking at a mistrial.

681
00:30:02.104 --> 00:30:03.560
And given that it is
the attorney general

682
00:30:03.584 --> 00:30:04.977
who is bringing this case

683
00:30:05.020 --> 00:30:07.893
and it seems like he's
got some skin in the game

684
00:30:08.763 --> 00:30:11.070
you can be sure he is

685
00:30:11.113 --> 00:30:13.812
perfectly happy to try
this again next year.

686
00:30:13.855 --> 00:30:16.815
Which leaves our client
on hold for a whole year.

687
00:30:16.858 --> 00:30:18.294
unable to move on with his life

688
00:30:18.338 --> 00:30:20.209
and his reputation destroyed.

689
00:30:20.253 --> 00:30:23.647
I'm-I'm confused. What
is it that we need?

690
00:30:23.691 --> 00:30:25.974
I mean. what is it that's gonna
turn this whole thing around?

691
00:30:25.998 --> 00:30:29.610
Just... [inhales] ...let
me know and I'll find it.

692
00:30:31.046 --> 00:30:33.570
A witness who will [inhales]

693
00:30:33.614 --> 00:30:37.052
take the stand and
say in a clear voice

694
00:30:37.096 --> 00:30:38.445
this whole thing was a setup.

695
00:30:38.488 --> 00:30:40.273
It exists not to right a wrong

696
00:30:40.316 --> 00:30:42.841
but to sideline a
political rival.

697
00:30:43.842 --> 00:30:45.017
[sighs]

698
00:30:45.060 --> 00:30:46.366
Anyway.

699
00:30:46.409 --> 00:30:49.543
I have got nothing
more to contribute.

700
00:30:49.586 --> 00:30:52.720
So I'm gonna go retire to my

701
00:30:52.763 --> 00:30:54.243
office couch.

702
00:30:54.287 --> 00:30:57.029
Ms. Rentzel. Ms. Morgan.
Mr. Palmer. Ms. James.

703
00:30:57.072 --> 00:30:58.334
Thank you.

704
00:30:59.945 --> 00:31:01.207
I have something.

705
00:31:01.250 --> 00:31:04.123
It's probably nothing.
I just found it curious.

706
00:31:04.166 --> 00:31:05.515
But I've been going through.

707
00:31:05.559 --> 00:31:07.169
Sherman's campaign
contribution logs.

708
00:31:07.213 --> 00:31:08.301
And for what it's worth.

709
00:31:08.344 --> 00:31:09.302
everything looks
on the up-and-up.

710
00:31:09.345 --> 00:31:10.869
And then I thought. "Hey".

711
00:31:10.912 --> 00:31:13.306
"what's good for the goose is
good for the gander." So then

712
00:31:13.349 --> 00:31:14.829
I started poking around

713
00:31:14.873 --> 00:31:17.397
the attorney general's
campaign contribution logs.

714
00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:19.616
And? Again. it's
probably nothing.

715
00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:22.968
But... he opened this
Senate exploratory account.

716
00:31:23.011 --> 00:31:24.851
a place where people can
donate to his campaign

717
00:31:24.883 --> 00:31:26.928
even before he
officially announces.

718
00:31:26.972 --> 00:31:28.930
And?

719
00:31:28.974 --> 00:31:32.281
You know who donated $2.500?

720
00:31:32.325 --> 00:31:33.674
Ken Kiehl.

721
00:31:33.717 --> 00:31:35.197
Who's Ken Kiehl?

722
00:31:35.241 --> 00:31:38.461
Well. he's a guy who. on
paper. worked for D.A. Sherman.

723
00:31:38.505 --> 00:31:41.160
And since Sherman was also
talking about a Senate run.

724
00:31:41.203 --> 00:31:43.162
it just... seemed odd to me

725
00:31:43.205 --> 00:31:45.729
that he'd be contributing
to a competitor.

726
00:31:46.905 --> 00:31:48.428
Ken Kiehl.

727
00:31:48.471 --> 00:31:51.257
Izzy's always talking about him.

728
00:31:51.300 --> 00:31:53.737
He recruited Benny
to run for D.A.

729
00:31:53.781 --> 00:31:55.826
♪

730
00:32:00.744 --> 00:32:04.226
Is this where you
volunteer for the campaign?

731
00:32:04.270 --> 00:32:05.749
Wow.

732
00:32:05.793 --> 00:32:07.142
[laughs]

733
00:32:07.186 --> 00:32:08.317
Send this to Ripley.

734
00:32:08.361 --> 00:32:09.623
He wouldn't believe it.

735
00:32:10.537 --> 00:32:11.930
Boss know you're here?

736
00:32:11.973 --> 00:32:13.105
Nope.

737
00:32:13.148 --> 00:32:15.063
[exhales]

738
00:32:15.107 --> 00:32:16.369
What can I do you for?

739
00:32:16.412 --> 00:32:18.023
I wanted to talk to you.

740
00:32:18.066 --> 00:32:20.808
You're still a lawyer. right?

741
00:32:20.851 --> 00:32:23.289
Yeah.

742
00:32:25.421 --> 00:32:26.945
There.

743
00:32:28.424 --> 00:32:30.513
I just hired you.

744
00:32:30.557 --> 00:32:33.777
I'd like to invoke
attorney-client privilege.

745
00:32:34.865 --> 00:32:35.865
♪

746
00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:43.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

747
00:32:44.310 --> 00:32:47.139
BAILIFF: All rise. The New
York State Superior Court

748
00:32:47.182 --> 00:32:48.618
is now in session.

749
00:32:48.662 --> 00:32:50.359
the Honorable Judge
Rand presiding.

750
00:32:50.403 --> 00:32:52.535
[gavel bangs]RAND:
Is the defense

751
00:32:52.579 --> 00:32:55.799
prepared to rest? Uh. we
moving on to closing arguments?

752
00:32:55.843 --> 00:32:57.279
CHUNK: With the
court's permission.

753
00:32:57.323 --> 00:33:00.065
we would actually like
to call one last witness.

754
00:33:00.108 --> 00:33:01.980
The defense would like to call

755
00:33:02.023 --> 00:33:04.156
Benjamin Colón to the stand.

756
00:33:04.199 --> 00:33:06.332
[door opens]

757
00:33:20.607 --> 00:33:22.174
[whispers]: Trust me.

758
00:33:23.914 --> 00:33:26.700
Good morning. Mr. Colón.Good
morning. Mr. Palmer.

759
00:33:26.743 --> 00:33:28.615
Now. do you know a prosecutor

760
00:33:28.658 --> 00:33:31.661
in the Manhattan D.A.'s
office named Kenneth Kiehl?

761
00:33:31.705 --> 00:33:34.142
I-I do. I know him well.

762
00:33:34.186 --> 00:33:37.145
In fact. he encouraged
me to run for the office

763
00:33:37.189 --> 00:33:40.540
that District Attorney
Sherman resigned.

764
00:33:40.583 --> 00:33:42.803
Objection. Relevance?

765
00:33:42.846 --> 00:33:44.848
Mr. Palmer.

766
00:33:44.892 --> 00:33:47.503
I assume this is
going somewhere.

767
00:33:47.547 --> 00:33:48.852
It is. Your Honor.

768
00:33:48.896 --> 00:33:50.680
And we'll get there in
the very near future.

769
00:33:50.724 --> 00:33:52.006
[chuckles] Yes. we
will. Your Honor.

770
00:33:52.030 --> 00:33:55.076
But I would ask for
a little leeway.

771
00:33:55.120 --> 00:33:57.122
Proceed.

772
00:33:58.210 --> 00:34:00.821
And to the best
of your knowledge.

773
00:34:00.864 --> 00:34:04.651
how long has A.D.A. Kiehl worked
in the Manhattan D.A.'s office?

774
00:34:04.694 --> 00:34:07.828
Uh. I believe he's been
there for about eight years.

775
00:34:07.871 --> 00:34:09.395
So. up until very recently.

776
00:34:09.438 --> 00:34:13.138
Mr. Sherman. my
client. was his boss?

777
00:34:13.181 --> 00:34:14.443
Yes.

778
00:34:14.487 --> 00:34:18.839
The defense would like
to offer into evidence

779
00:34:18.882 --> 00:34:22.103
a page from the
attorney general's.

780
00:34:22.147 --> 00:34:24.497
Senate campaign accounts record.

781
00:34:24.540 --> 00:34:26.412
It shows that Mr. Ken Kiehl.

782
00:34:26.455 --> 00:34:29.371
who worked for then
District Attorney Sherman.

783
00:34:29.415 --> 00:34:32.113
made a donation of $2.500

784
00:34:32.157 --> 00:34:33.854
to the man who not only

785
00:34:33.897 --> 00:34:37.205
is seeking the same
office as his boss

786
00:34:37.249 --> 00:34:40.426
but also who brought this
legal action against him.

787
00:34:41.253 --> 00:34:43.168
So entered. CHUNK:
Now. Mr. Colón.

788
00:34:43.211 --> 00:34:45.996
does the news of this
contribution surprise you?

789
00:34:46.040 --> 00:34:47.781
It might have two weeks ago.

790
00:34:47.824 --> 00:34:50.610
but based on a conversation
we had the other night.

791
00:34:50.653 --> 00:34:53.395
uh. it makes perfect sense.

792
00:34:53.439 --> 00:34:55.136
And why is that?

793
00:34:55.180 --> 00:34:58.966
Well. Mr. Kiehl explained
to me that Mr. Sherman

794
00:34:59.009 --> 00:35:02.622
had been a thorn in the side
of many people in government.

795
00:35:02.665 --> 00:35:05.538
most especially the
attorney general.

796
00:35:05.581 --> 00:35:07.714
Objection! Relevance.

797
00:35:07.757 --> 00:35:11.631
Neither this... Mr. Kiehl
nor the attorney general

798
00:35:11.674 --> 00:35:13.502
are on trial here.
CHUNK: Your Honor.

799
00:35:13.546 --> 00:35:15.983
the defense is trying to prove
that there was a conspiracy

800
00:35:16.026 --> 00:35:18.638
to oust District Attorney
Sherman from office

801
00:35:18.681 --> 00:35:22.294
and to effectively remove him
from the upcoming Senate race.

802
00:35:22.337 --> 00:35:23.512
Mr. Kiehl's comments

803
00:35:23.556 --> 00:35:25.688
go directly to the
heart of that matter.

804
00:35:25.732 --> 00:35:28.343
I concur. Objection overruled.

805
00:35:28.387 --> 00:35:30.476
You may continue. Mr. Palmer.

806
00:35:30.519 --> 00:35:33.348
And did Mr. Kiehl tell you

807
00:35:33.392 --> 00:35:35.089
why the attorney general

808
00:35:35.133 --> 00:35:36.917
and so many other
people in government

809
00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:41.095
wanted to get rid of
District Attorney Sherman?

810
00:35:42.879 --> 00:35:46.361
He said he was too straight.

811
00:35:46.405 --> 00:35:47.928
Basically. too honest.

812
00:35:47.971 --> 00:35:49.712
Stood in the way
of too many things.

813
00:35:49.756 --> 00:35:53.194
too many people. too much money.

814
00:35:53.238 --> 00:35:55.370
He had to go.

815
00:35:55.414 --> 00:35:57.633
[quietly]: Thank you. Benny.

816
00:35:57.677 --> 00:36:00.070
CHUNK: He was too honest.

817
00:36:00.114 --> 00:36:03.117
Getting in the way
of too much money.

818
00:36:03.161 --> 00:36:05.424
He had to go.

819
00:36:08.122 --> 00:36:10.777
No further questions
for this witness.

820
00:36:17.349 --> 00:36:19.394
Mr. Colón.

821
00:36:19.438 --> 00:36:23.268
isn't it true that
up until last week.

822
00:36:23.311 --> 00:36:26.009
you worked for the very firm

823
00:36:26.053 --> 00:36:29.230
that is now defending
Mr. Sherman?

824
00:36:29.274 --> 00:36:30.579
That is true.

825
00:36:30.623 --> 00:36:35.018
Then why should anyone
on this jury believe you?

826
00:36:35.062 --> 00:36:37.804
The man who just questioned
you is your friend.

827
00:36:37.847 --> 00:36:40.589
The man he works
for is the father

828
00:36:40.633 --> 00:36:42.112
of your niece.

829
00:36:42.156 --> 00:36:45.768
The man they're defending
was someone you worked for

830
00:36:45.812 --> 00:36:48.989
at the end of your career
as a city prosecutor.

831
00:36:51.513 --> 00:36:54.037
And your point is?

832
00:36:54.081 --> 00:36:57.258
I have friends. so I
shouldn't be believed?

833
00:36:57.302 --> 00:36:59.042
Yes.

834
00:36:59.086 --> 00:37:02.307
The man who was questioning
me is my friend.

835
00:37:02.350 --> 00:37:04.134
A good friend.

836
00:37:04.178 --> 00:37:05.919
And the man he is
here defending...

837
00:37:05.962 --> 00:37:08.574
Turns out he's a friend. too.

838
00:37:08.617 --> 00:37:10.619
Did me a huge kindness once.

839
00:37:10.663 --> 00:37:13.013
and I didn't even know about it.

840
00:37:13.056 --> 00:37:15.276
Now. that is a real friend.

841
00:37:16.799 --> 00:37:19.019
And my niece's father?

842
00:37:20.107 --> 00:37:24.024
Maybe the best friend I
have in the whole world.

843
00:37:24.067 --> 00:37:27.201
Maybe the best friend
I'll ever have.

844
00:37:28.289 --> 00:37:31.597
You want to know why
you should believe me?

845
00:37:31.640 --> 00:37:33.425
I have everything to lose

846
00:37:33.468 --> 00:37:36.079
and nothing to gain
by coming here.

847
00:37:36.123 --> 00:37:37.864
As I'm sure you know.

848
00:37:37.907 --> 00:37:40.475
I'm running to
replace the defendant

849
00:37:40.519 --> 00:37:42.825
as the city's district attorney.

850
00:37:42.869 --> 00:37:47.482
And what you may or may not know
is that I am up in the polls.

851
00:37:47.526 --> 00:37:50.224
I am poised to win.

852
00:37:50.268 --> 00:37:54.010
Nevertheless. I
believe so strongly

853
00:37:54.054 --> 00:37:55.882
in what I'm telling you.

854
00:37:55.925 --> 00:37:57.492
I believe so strongly

855
00:37:57.536 --> 00:38:01.322
in former District Attorney
Sherman's innocence

856
00:38:01.366 --> 00:38:03.281
that...

857
00:38:03.324 --> 00:38:06.980
I'm officially
withdrawing from the race.

858
00:38:08.547 --> 00:38:11.419
and am supporting
any and all efforts

859
00:38:11.463 --> 00:38:13.378
to return Mr. Sherman
to an office

860
00:38:13.421 --> 00:38:17.817
he never should have been forced
to give up in the first place.

861
00:38:21.516 --> 00:38:23.039
[gallery whispering]

862
00:38:23.083 --> 00:38:26.347
How's that for a
reason to believe me?

863
00:38:26.391 --> 00:38:29.002
Next question.

864
00:38:30.743 --> 00:38:32.875
You heard the man. Counselor.

865
00:38:32.919 --> 00:38:35.791
Next question.

866
00:38:38.577 --> 00:38:41.101
[Benny sighs]

867
00:38:42.407 --> 00:38:44.713
Jury was out in all
of eight minutes.

868
00:38:44.757 --> 00:38:46.280
That must be some
kind of record.

869
00:38:46.324 --> 00:38:48.543
Yeah. congrats on the
verdict. Not guilty.

870
00:38:48.587 --> 00:38:49.892
That's got to feel great.

871
00:38:49.936 --> 00:38:51.633
No. congrats to you.

872
00:38:51.677 --> 00:38:53.113
And thank you.

873
00:38:53.156 --> 00:38:54.375
I don't know how to thank you.

874
00:38:54.419 --> 00:38:57.639
Well. I'm not the
man you should thank.

875
00:38:57.683 --> 00:38:59.902
Oh. no. I beg to differ.

876
00:38:59.946 --> 00:39:01.382
[Benny chuckles]

877
00:39:01.426 --> 00:39:02.731
Thanks for doing that.

878
00:39:02.775 --> 00:39:04.690
Thanks for putting your
dream on hold for me.

879
00:39:04.733 --> 00:39:05.908
I owe you.

880
00:39:05.952 --> 00:39:07.823
I've owed you for
years and years

881
00:39:07.867 --> 00:39:09.390
and didn't even know it.

882
00:39:09.434 --> 00:39:10.957
Now we're even.

883
00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:12.674
CHUNK: I just got a text from
the attorney general's office.

884
00:39:12.698 --> 00:39:15.178
They're issuing warrants
for Investigator Martel

885
00:39:15.222 --> 00:39:16.658
and Ken Kiehl's arrest.

886
00:39:16.702 --> 00:39:18.138
Perjury. conspiracy.

887
00:39:18.181 --> 00:39:20.270
obstruction of justice
and witness tampering.

888
00:39:20.314 --> 00:39:21.794
Going after everybody
but himself.

889
00:39:21.837 --> 00:39:22.945
[Chunk chuckles][elevator
bell dings]

890
00:39:22.969 --> 00:39:24.405
Let's get some food.

891
00:39:24.449 --> 00:39:26.538
This one's on me.
BULL: Yes. indeed.

892
00:39:26.581 --> 00:39:29.454
Text me where you end
up. I'll meet you later.

893
00:39:30.324 --> 00:39:31.891
Uh. hey. guys. you know what?

894
00:39:31.934 --> 00:39:34.154
I will meet you there as well.

895
00:39:38.288 --> 00:39:40.639
Speaking of getting
your job back...

896
00:39:40.682 --> 00:39:42.945
I should warn you.

897
00:39:42.989 --> 00:39:46.209
In light of your
abominable behavior.

898
00:39:46.253 --> 00:39:48.211
I'm gonna make this hard on you.

899
00:39:48.255 --> 00:39:50.213
I'm not taking a penny less

900
00:39:50.257 --> 00:39:51.713
than half the money
you used to pay me.

901
00:39:51.737 --> 00:39:52.955
Sorry. no. Double or nothing.

902
00:39:52.999 --> 00:39:54.957
[exhales] Drive a hard bargain.

903
00:39:55.001 --> 00:39:56.524
[chuckles]

904
00:39:57.830 --> 00:39:59.788
I missed you. man.

905
00:39:59.832 --> 00:40:01.834
Yeah. I'm an idiot.

906
00:40:01.877 --> 00:40:04.053
I know you are.

907
00:40:05.664 --> 00:40:08.797
I got to find Izzy. There's
something with the sitter.

908
00:40:08.841 --> 00:40:11.365
But. uh. I'll catch up with you.

909
00:40:11.409 --> 00:40:12.888
Yeah.

910
00:40:20.287 --> 00:40:23.159
IZZY: I know this girl.

911
00:40:23.203 --> 00:40:25.901
You ditch your friends.

912
00:40:25.945 --> 00:40:29.122
buy her a couple of drinks. and.

913
00:40:29.165 --> 00:40:33.169
and she's gonna let you take
her home and share her bed.

914
00:40:33.953 --> 00:40:35.781
Really?

915
00:40:35.824 --> 00:40:37.478
You think I'm just
gonna roll over

916
00:40:37.522 --> 00:40:39.393
and let you have
your way with me?

917
00:40:41.264 --> 00:40:44.006
What would you like to drink?
'Cause I can call ahead

918
00:40:44.050 --> 00:40:46.052
and have them sitting
on the bar for us.

919
00:40:51.274 --> 00:40:53.320
What was your name
again?[chuckles]

920
00:40:59.108 --> 00:41:02.024
I don't understand. If Chunk
didn't tell you about Benny

921
00:41:02.068 --> 00:41:04.374
beating the bejesus out
of that guy. then who did?

922
00:41:04.418 --> 00:41:06.202
You know. I can't tell you.

923
00:41:06.246 --> 00:41:08.204
It's attorney-client privilege.

924
00:41:08.248 --> 00:41:11.947
[keys jangle]Well. I don't understand.
'cause you're not an attorney.

925
00:41:11.991 --> 00:41:13.862
Um. I'm gonna go
check on Astrid.

926
00:41:13.906 --> 00:41:16.517
Will you pay the sitter? I think
she's probably in the kitchen.

927
00:41:16.561 --> 00:41:19.085
I do as I'm told.

928
00:41:21.087 --> 00:41:23.655
[sighs. clears throat]

929
00:41:26.788 --> 00:41:28.573
Judge Rand?

930
00:41:29.356 --> 00:41:32.794
What are you doing in my
kitchen at 11:00 at night?

931
00:41:32.838 --> 00:41:34.056
I don't know.

932
00:41:34.100 --> 00:41:35.928
I'm a judge.

933
00:41:35.971 --> 00:41:39.192
Some lady told me a
couple of crazy kids

934
00:41:39.235 --> 00:41:40.759
want to get married tonight.

935
00:41:40.802 --> 00:41:42.543
ALL: Surprise!

936
00:41:42.587 --> 00:41:44.110
[laughing. cheering]

937
00:41:49.463 --> 00:41:52.422
CHUNK: Come on. Yeah!
You people are crazy.

938
00:41:52.466 --> 00:41:55.861
A surprise wedding in
a kitchen? CHUNK: Yes.

939
00:41:55.904 --> 00:41:57.950
Isn't it romantic?

940
00:41:57.993 --> 00:42:00.387
[whispers]: It is romantic.

941
00:42:07.829 --> 00:42:09.352
Dearly beloved.

942
00:42:09.396 --> 00:42:11.572
we are gathered here tonight

943
00:42:11.616 --> 00:42:14.444
in this pretty damn
romantic kitchen

944
00:42:14.488 --> 00:42:16.359
to witness the joining of Jason

945
00:42:16.403 --> 00:42:17.796
and Isabella

946
00:42:17.839 --> 00:42:19.537
in the sacred
covenant of marriage.

947
00:42:20.305 --> 00:43:20.222
